# English Vocabulary O/X
> Common word meanings
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.language.vocabulary/

The word 'aquatic' relates to water. | O | 'Aquatic' describes things that live in or relate to water.
A 'decade' is a period of ten years. | O | A decade means a span of ten years.
'Enormous' means extremely large. | O | 'Enormous' describes something very big in size or amount.
A 'herbivore' is an animal that eats plants. | O | A herbivore is an animal whose diet is mainly plants.
'Ancient' means very old, from long ago. | O | 'Ancient' describes something belonging to the very distant past.
To 'increase' means to become larger or greater in amount. | O | 'Increase' means to grow in size, number, or amount.
The word 'gigantic' means very small. | X | 'Gigantic' means extremely large, the opposite of small.
A 'century' is a period of ten years. | X | A century is a period of one hundred years; ten years is a decade.
'Optional' means that something is required. | X | 'Optional' means something is a choice and not required.
A 'carnivore' is an animal that eats only plants. | X | A carnivore is an animal that eats meat; a plant-eater is a herbivore.
'Ascend' means to go down. | X | 'Ascend' means to move upward; going down is to 'descend'.
'Visible' means impossible to see. | X | 'Visible' means able to be seen.
'Fragile' means easily broken. | O | 'Fragile' describes something delicate that can break or be damaged easily.
'Annual' means happening once a year. | O | 'Annual' describes something that occurs every year, like an annual festival or report.
'Rapid' means very slow. | X | 'Rapid' means very fast or quick, the opposite of slow.
A 'pessimist' is a person who expects the best to happen. | X | A pessimist tends to expect the worst; a person who expects the best is an optimist.
'Transparent' describes something you can see through. | O | 'Transparent' means clear enough for light to pass through, like glass.
'Fiction' refers to true stories about real events. | X | Fiction is invented storytelling from the imagination; writing about real events is nonfiction.
A 'pediatrician' is a doctor who treats children. | O | A pediatrician specializes in the medical care of babies, children, and teenagers.
A 'pharmacist' is a person who repairs cars. | X | A pharmacist prepares and dispenses medicines; a person who repairs cars is a mechanic.
To 'purchase' something means to buy it. | O | 'Purchase' is a more formal word for buying something with money.
'Courageous' means brave. | O | 'Courageous' describes someone who shows bravery in the face of danger or difficulty.
'Arrogant' means humble and modest. | X | 'Arrogant' describes someone with an exaggerated sense of their own importance, the opposite of humble.
'Departure' means the act of arriving somewhere. | X | 'Departure' is the act of leaving; the act of arriving is 'arrival'.
A 'bilingual' person can speak two languages. | O | 'Bilingual' means able to use two languages; the prefix 'bi-' means two.
'Fatal' means completely harmless. | X | 'Fatal' means causing death, as in a fatal accident, so it is far from harmless.
'Exhausted' means extremely tired. | O | 'Exhausted' describes being drained of energy, far more tired than usual.
'Generous' means unwilling to share with others. | X | 'Generous' means freely giving or sharing; someone unwilling to share is stingy.
'Temporary' means lasting forever. | X | 'Temporary' means lasting only for a limited time; something lasting forever is permanent.
To 'postpone' means to delay something until later. | O | 'Postpone' means to move an event to a later time, like postponing a meeting.
'Vacant' means full of people. | X | 'Vacant' means empty or unoccupied, like a vacant seat or room.
'Nocturnal' animals are active mainly at night. | O | 'Nocturnal' describes creatures like owls and bats that sleep by day and are active at night.
An 'author' is a person who writes books. | O | An author is the writer of a book, article, or other written work.
To 'whisper' means to shout loudly. | X | 'Whisper' means to speak very softly and quietly, the opposite of shouting.
A 'punctual' person is always late. | X | 'Punctual' means arriving or doing things exactly on time, not late.
'Identical' means exactly the same. | O | 'Identical' describes things that are exactly alike, such as identical twins.
